></a></figure></div><p><span>Caesar is referring, of course, to Alexander t=
he Great.</span><span class=3D"footnote-hovercard-target"><a class=3D"footn=
ote-anchor" data-component-name=3D"FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id=3D"footnote-anch=
or-1-136306805" href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/evil-eyes-and-tall-=
poppies#footnote-1-136306805" target=3D"_self" rel=3D"">1</a></span></p><p>=
Caesar lamented the fact that despite his immense accomplishments, he felt =
diminished when he compared himself to this earlier historical leader.</p><=
p><span>Interestingly, </span><a href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/ca=
esar-and-the-dominance-oriented" rel=3D"">Caesar himself</a><span> was a vi=
ctim of this kind of social comparison, at least in the Shakespearean versi=
on of the story, which is based on the historian Plutarch=E2=80=99s account=
.</span></p><p>Caesar had a friend named Cassius, who was a Roman senator. =
Cassius told another senator named Brutus a story from his childhood. The s=
tory was that when they were young boys, Cassius saved Caesar from drowning=
.</p><p>Ever since then, Cassius felt superior to Caesar. However, Caesar h=
ad recently become the leader of Rome and became widely beloved by the mass=
es. Cassius envied him for this. This motivated Cassius to set in motion th=
e events that eventually led to Caesar=E2=80=99s assassination in the Roman=
 senate.</p><p>Early in his career, Caesar felt he had not ascended high en=
ough. And later, he was killed because others thought he had ascended too h=
igh.</p><div><hr></div><p>I open with this story to illustrate the idea of =
social comparison orientation. Simply defined, it is the inclination to com=
pare yourself with others, especially with regard to social status.</p><p><=
span>A couple of sample items in the social comparison scale </span><a href=
=3D"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34153569/" rel=3D"">are</a><span> =E2=
=80=9CI often compare myself with others with respect to what I have accomp=
lished in life=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CI often compare how I am doing sociall=
y (social skills, popularity) with other people.=E2=80=9D</span></p><p>Soci=
al comparison, by definition, is relative. Here is a question often used in=
 these kinds of scales.</p><p><span>Suppose you are presented with two </sp=
an><a href=3D"https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2013-42146-018" rel=3D"">optio=
ns</a><span>:</span></p><p>A. You get 2 weeks of vacation; your coworkers g=
et 1 week</p><p>B. You get 4 weeks of vacation; your coworkers get 8 weeks<=
/p><p>A sensible, rational, objective person should choose B. One week of v=
acation versus 4 weeks is a no-brainer. But a surprisingly high number of p=
eople will choose A over B.</p><p>Consider the reality of working in an env=
ironment in which you know everyone gets twice as much vacation time as you=
. It=E2=80=99s unfair. And as we=E2=80=99ve discussed before, our preoccupa=
tion with the idea of fairness is in part rooted in concerns about status. =
&nbsp;</p><p>So what are some of the traits associated with social comparis=
on orientation?</p><p><span>Unsurprisingly, social comparison orientation i=
s associated with the </span><a href=3D"https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2016=
-11948-001" rel=3D"">Dark Triad personality traits</a><span> (psychopathy, =
narcissism, Machiavellianism), </span><a href=3D"https://psycnet.apa.org/re=
cord/2014-41315-006" rel=3D"">fear of failure</a><span>, interest in exhibi=
ting status, </span><a href=3D"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34153569/" r=
el=3D"">FoMo</a><span> (Fear of Missing Out), </span><a href=3D"https://jou=
rnals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/1948550620947294?journalCode=3Dsppa" rel=
=3D"">utilitarian moral preferences</a><span>, malicious envy, and benign e=
nvy. We=E2=80=99ll discuss the difference between these two forms of envy l=
ater.</span></p><p>The utilitarian finding is interesting. When you present=
 trolley problems to people high on social comparison orientation, they are=
 more likely to report that they would flip the switch to kill one person o=
r push the fat man off the bridge in order to save five people. They seem t=
o favor cold calculations for decision-making, which may be why they tend t=
o score highly on psychopathy.</p><p>Narcissism is unsurprising. People who=
 compare themselves with others are more likely to be preoccupied with thei=
r social image and want others to admire them and think highly of them.</p>=
<p>This is of course related to fear of failure. Failure means that you com=
e off looking comparatively worse than others. Social comparers are interes=
ted in status displays, that=E2=80=99s not a surprise given the link with n=
arcissism.</p><p><span>In fact, some researchers have </span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://global.oup.com/academic/product/identifying-and-understanding-the-narc=
issistic-personality-9780195148732?cc=3Dus&amp;lang=3Den&amp;" rel=3D"">fou=
nd</a><span> that narcissistically-oriented people often report intense rea=
ctions to the perception of others=E2=80=99 envy. They experience a hidden =
sadistic satisfaction in causing a sense of inferiority and painful feeling=
s in others.</span></p><p>Social comparers report greater levels of Fear of=
 Missing Out, because if they are left out or excluded, this reflects poorl=
y on them. Most people want to be a part of the excitement, but social comp=
arers have an especially intense desire to be among those who are seen. &nb=
sp;</p><p>And this brings us to envy.</p><p><span>What is envy? Plainly, it=
 is the emotional consequence of upward social comparison. Envy is an emoti=
on that </span><a href=3D"https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2018-21510-018" re=
l=3D"">regulates</a><span> the navigation of status hierarchies.</span></p>=
<p>It is a painful emotion. People might say they will occasionally feel pr=
ide, or greed, or lust, but seldom do people confess to feelings of envy. T=
o confess to envy is to acknowledge that you believe someone else has more =
status than you. Few people are eager to intentionally lower themselves in =
this way.</p><p>Envy is an unpleasant feeling, as many of your emotions are=
. But negative emotions are evolutionarily adaptive. Envy alerts you when y=
ou might be falling too low on the status ladder. It is a kind of status le=
veling mechanism.</p><p><span>Here=E2=80=99s how some psychologists have </=
span><a href=3D"https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2018-21510-018" rel=3D"">des=
cribed</a><span> it:</span></p><blockquote><p><em>=E2=80=9CAt its core, env=
y is born out of the perceived danger to lose respect and social influence =
in the eyes of others=E2=80=A6envy=E2=80=99s function may be to foster the =
motivations to re-gain status or harm the superior position of others.=E2=
=80=9D</em></p></blockquote><p><span>What does envy look like? Here=E2=80=
=99s a still from season 1 of the superb television series </span><em>Mad M=
en</em><span>. </span></p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container"><figure>=
